Where has the time gone... Just over 2 years ago, I said yes to a new opportunity and wow, what a ride it has been. There have been incredible highs and to be expected, some lows but I have enjoyed the journey and pleased I took the leap. I have met some incredible people along the way. 

Once in a Lifetime Holidays is a still a relatively new company, but has proven that with hard work you can achieve your dreams. Over the past year we have won 2 industry awards and now as team of 6, we are thriving. 

I couldn't have done it without the support of people around me, my friends and family and most of all my supportive husband believing in me (and putting up with me). 

Huge thanks goes out to the best AWARD WINNING TEAM I could ask for; their determination and drive to succeed is inspiring and they are always there to help push you and pick you up when you need it, Louise, Kim, Michelle, Dave and especially Joan for taking a chance on me. 

Of course my business wouldn't be what it is without YOU my lovely clients, and I thank each and every one of you for your business and your referrals. It means the world to me! 

As today marks 2 years since the start of my little business, I want to give you the opportunity to win a bottle of fizz to raise a glass with me to the future of Emma Handley - Once in a Lifetime Holidays ğŸ¥‚

1. ANGKOR WAT
Angkor wat is the world's largest religious monument. This Khmer construction is an architectural marvel with 3,000 apsaras carved.

Angkor wat was built during the reign of Suryavarman II, in the first half of 12 th century and is dedicated to Lord Vishnu.

The outer limits of Angkor Wat are set by its broad most, faced in laterite and sandstone and Is the largest temple at Angkor complex stretching for 200 hectares.

Angkor Wat also replicates the spatial universe in miniature. The central tower is Mount Meru, with its surrounding smaller peaks, bounded in turn by continents (the lower courtyards) and the oceans (the moat). The seven-headed naga (mythical serpent) becomes a symbolic rainbow bridge for humankind to reach the abode of the gods.

Process involved in building the mighty Angkor Wat:
The sandstone blocks from which Angkor Wat was built were quarried from the holy mountain of Phnom Kulen, more than 50km away, and floated down the Siem Reap River on rafts. The logistics of such an operation are mind-blowing, consuming the labor of thousands. According to inscriptions, the construction of Angkor Wat involved 300,000 workers and 6000 elephants. It was still not fully completed.

Angkor Wat is surrounded by a 190m-wide moat, which forms a giant rectangle measuring 1.5km by 1.3km. From the west, a sandstone causeway crosses the moat.

Cost of Angkor Pass: $37 for 1 day, $62 for 3 days(can be used over a period of 10 days), $72 for 7 days (can be used over a period of 1 month)

Mode of transport: I used a cab (50 USD per day).

Dress code: shoulder and legs should be covered or else they would not allow I side the temple.

Angkor Wat, Siem Reap, Cambodia
